<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>1393</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>def-001O</addr>  <route>def-001O.xml</route>   <title>Antisymmetric Matrix</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>
    A square matrix <tex>A</tex> is antisymmetric if it is equal to the negative of its transpose:
    <tex display="block">
        A = -A^T
    </tex>
    This also implies <tex>A^{-1} A^T = -I</tex></p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>1394</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>def-001M</addr>  <route>def-001M.xml</route>   <title>Symmetric and Antisymmetric Part</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>
    Any square matrix <tex>A</tex> can be written as the sum of a symmetric and antisymmetric matrix:
    <tex display="block">
        A = A_S + A_A
    </tex>
    where <tex>A_S</tex> is the <strong>symmetric part</strong> and <tex>A_A</tex> is the <strong>antisymmetric part</strong>.
    <tex display="block">
        A_S =  \frac {1}{2}(A + A^T)
    </tex>
    where <tex>A_S</tex> is a <link href="def-001N.xml" type="local" addr="def-001N" title="Symmetric Matrix">symmetric matrix</link>
    <tex display="block">
        A_A =  \frac {1}{2}(A - A^T)
    </tex>
    where <tex>A_A</tex> is an <link href="def-001O.xml" type="local" addr="def-001O" title="Antisymmetric Matrix">antisymmetric matrix</link></p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>